A '''philosophical poet''' is an author or scholar who employs [[Poetry|poetic devices, styles, or forms]] to explore subjects common to the field of [[philosophy]]. Their writing often addresses questions related to the meaning of life, the nature of being ([[ontology]]), theories of knowledge and knowing ([[epistemology]]), principles of beauty ([[aesthetics]]), first principles of things ([[metaphysics]]) or the existence of God. Some may make broad philosophical inquires and engage with diverse philosophical topics throughout their poetry, while others may concentrate within one branch of philosophical poetry. For example, [[Dante Alighieri|Dante]] is considered by some to be both a philosophical poet, in a general sense, as well as a metaphysical poet.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2QbBcPW-JF8C&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=philosophical+poet+definition&source=bl&ots=yv0rOa2M80&sig=gqL4IWFwaFATG3oO3HQlUog55U8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQv5ypgdPMAhWH4IMKHee2DIQ4ChDoAQgmMAI#v=onepage&q=philosophical%2520poet%2520definition&f=false|title=The Early T. S. Eliot and Western Philosophy|last=Habib|first=Rafey|date=1999-06-28|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521624336|language=en}}</ref>
Although a group discussion may provide fruitful conditions for some to explore philosophical themes, poetry may be seen an alternative entry into philosophical thinking.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LFogBQAAQBAJ|title=The Philosophy Shop: Ideas, activities and questions to get people, young and old, thinking philosophically|last=Worley|first=Peter|date=2012-09-27|publisher=Crown House Publishing|isbn=9781781350614|language=en}}</ref> Children and young writers may find it easier to begin writing philosophical poetry if they start by using poetic styles other than rhyme, such as repetitive form, since rhyme can be distracting and may interfere with the free flow of their philosophical thoughts.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LFogBQAAQBAJ|title=The Philosophy Shop: Ideas, activities and questions to get people, young and old, thinking philosophically|last=Worley|first=Peter|date=2012-09-27|publisher=Crown House Publishing|isbn=9781781350614|language=en}}</ref> Most, but not all, philosophical poets do eventually develop one preferred form of philosophical verse when it comes to the style of their writing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kenyonreview.org/2012/01/two-philosophical-poets-on-t-s-eliot-and-kay-ryan/|title=Two Philosophical Poets: On T. S. Eliot and Kay Ryan « Kenyon Review Blog|website=www.kenyonreview.org|access-date=2016-05-11}}</ref> For example, [[Rumi]] and [[Hafez|Hafiz]] often utilize the single [[Verse (poetry)|verse]] form, while [[Emily Dickinson|Dickinson]] usually adheres to the [[Quatrain|quatrain form]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kenyonreview.org/2012/01/two-philosophical-poets-on-t-s-eliot-and-kay-ryan/|title=Two Philosophical Poets: On T. S. Eliot and Kay Ryan « Kenyon Review Blog|website=www.kenyonreview.org|access-date=2016-05-12}}</ref> Philosophical poets hail from both the Eastern and Western traditions.
==Notable Philosophical Poets==<!-- New links in alphabetical order please --> * [[Dante Alighieri]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/threephilosophic00santuoft|title=Three philosophical poets: Lucretius, Dante, and Goethe|last=Santayana|first=George|date=1910-01-01|publisher=Cambridge Harvard University}}</ref> * [[William Blake]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VMlgCgAAQBAJ|title=Blake's Heroic Argument|last=Fuller|first=David|date=2015-08-14|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317381341|language=en}}</ref> * [[Emily Dickinson]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kenyonreview.org/2012/01/two-philosophical-poets-on-t-s-eliot-and-kay-ryan/|title=Two Philosophical Poets: On T. S. Eliot and Kay Ryan « Kenyon Review Blog|website=www.kenyonreview.org|access-date=2016-05-12}}</ref> * [[T. S. Eliot|T.S. Elio]]<nowiki/>t<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kenyonreview.org/2012/01/two-philosophical-poets-on-t-s-eliot-and-kay-ryan/|title=Two Philosophical Poets: On T. S. Eliot and Kay Ryan « Kenyon Review Blog|website=www.kenyonreview.org|access-date=2016-05-11}}</ref> * [[Johann Wolfgang von Goethe|Johann Wolfgang Goethe]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/threephilosophic00santuoft|title=Three philosophical poets: Lucretius, Dante, and Goethe|last=Santayana|first=George|date=1910-01-01|publisher=Cambridge Harvard University}}</ref> * [[Njegoš]] * [[Hafez|Hafiz]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kenyonreview.org/2012/01/two-philosophical-poets-on-t-s-eliot-and-kay-ryan/|title=Two Philosophical Poets: On T. S. Eliot and Kay Ryan « Kenyon Review Blog|website=www.kenyonreview.org|access-date=2016-05-12}}</ref> * [[Lucretius]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/threephilosophic00santuoft|title=Three philosophical poets: Lucretius, Dante, and Goethe|last=Santayana|first=George|date=1910-01-01|publisher=Cambridge Harvard University}}</ref> * [[Kay Ryan]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kenyonreview.org/2012/01/two-philosophical-poets-on-t